> **Tip:**&#x20;
>
> MacOS Error
>
> MacOS users might see the following error after running the preceding
> commands:
>
> ```sh
> dyld[54430]: Library not loaded: @rpath/libmongocxx._noabi.dylib
> ```
>
> To resolve this error, use the `-Wl`,\`\`-rpath\`\` linker option to set
> the `@rpath`, as shown in the following code:
>
> ```sh
> c++ --std=c++17 CreateIndex.cpp -Wl,-rpath,/usr/local/lib/ $(pkg-config --cflags --libs libmongocxx) -o ./app.out
> ./app.out
> ```

The MongoDB Search dateFacet type takes the following parameters:

| Option     | Type   | Necessity | Description                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       | Default |
| ---------- | ------ | --------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------- |
| type       | string | Required  | Human-readable label that identifies this field type. Value must be token.                                                                                                                                                                                        |         |
| normalizer | string | Optional  | Type of transformation to perform on the field value. Value can be one of the following:lowercase - to transform text values in string fields to lowercase.none - to not perform any transformation.If you don't set this option explicitly, it defaults to none. | none    |

The following index definition examples use collections in the
[sample data sets](available-sample-datasets). After you
[Load Sample Data Into Atlas](load-sample-data), you can use
these examples to index fields as the dateFacet type.

To learn how to set up and run the following example code, see
Define the Index for the token Type.

Index as token Type Only Example

The following index definition indexes string values in the
`title` field as MongoDB Search dateFacet type and converts the
field value to `lowercase`, which allows you to do the
following:

- Perform case-insensitive sort, as specified by the
  `normalizer`, on the `title` field.

- Run exact match queries on the `title` field using the
  following operators:

  - [equals](equals-ref)

  - [in](in-ref)

  - [range](range-ref)

```cpp
#include <iostream>

#include <bsoncxx/builder/basic/document.hpp>
#include <bsoncxx/json.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/client.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/instance.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/uri.hpp>

using bsoncxx::builder::basic::kvp;
using bsoncxx::builder::basic::make_document;


int main(){

    mongocxx::instance instance;
    mongocxx::uri uri("<connection string>");
    mongocxx::client client(uri);

    auto db = client["sample_mflix"];
    auto collection = db["movies"];

    // instantiate a ``mongocxx::search_index_view`` on your collection
    auto siv = collection.search_indexes();

    {
        auto name = "default";
        auto definition = make_document(
            kvp("mappings", make_document(
                kvp("dynamic", false),
                kvp("fields", make_document(
                    kvp("title", make_document(
                        kvp("type", "token"),
                        kvp("normalizer", "lowercase")
                    ))
                ))
            ))
        );

        auto model = mongocxx::search_index_model(name, definition.view());

        // Create the search index
        auto result = siv.create_one(model);
        std::cout << "New index name: " << result << std::endl;
    }
}
```

Index as Multiple Types Example

The following index definition indexes the `genres` field as
`string` and `token` types to return the following:

- Search results for queries using MongoDB Search operators like
  [text](text-ref), [Phrase](phrase-ref), and other operators that
  perform text search on the `genres` field.

- Sorted results for queries using the [$search](pipe.$search)
  [sorting](sort-ref) option on the `genres` field.

- Exact matches for queries using MongoDB Search operators like
  [equals](equals-ref), [in](in-ref), and [range](range-ref).

```cpp
#include <iostream>

#include <bsoncxx/builder/basic/document.hpp>
#include <bsoncxx/json.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/client.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/instance.hpp>
#include <mongocxx/uri.hpp>

using bsoncxx::builder::basic::kvp;
using bsoncxx::builder::basic::make_document;


int main(){

    mongocxx::instance instance;
    mongocxx::uri uri("<connection string>");
    mongocxx::client client(uri);

    auto db = client["sample_mflix"];
    auto collection = db["movies"];

    // instantiate a ``mongocxx::search_index_view`` on your collection
    auto siv = collection.search_indexes();

    {
        auto name = "default";
        auto definition = make_document(
            kvp("mappings", make_document(
                kvp("dynamic", false),
                kvp("fields", make_document(
                    kvp("genres", [](bsoncxx::builder::basic::sub_array array) {
                        array.append(make_document(
                            kvp("type", "string")
                        ));
                        array.append(make_document(
                            kvp("type", "token")
                        ));
                    })
                ))
            ))
        );

        auto model = mongocxx::search_index_model(name, definition.view());

        // Create the search index
        auto result = siv.create_one(model);
        std::cout << "New index name: " << result << std::endl;
    }
}
```

You must use the MongoDB Search `token` type to index [string](manual/reference/bson-types) fields to enable sorting and faceting
on these fields. Then, you can perform the following actions:

- Use the `sort` option in your query
  to sort the results by the indexed field. To learn more, see
  [sorting](sort-ref).

- Use the `facet` collector in your query to group the results by the
  indexed field. To learn more, see [How to Use Facets with MongoDB Search](facet-tutorial).

Additionally, you must index string fields as the `token` type
in order to use the [equals](equals-ref), [in](in-ref)
and [range](range-ref) operators. To learn more, see the
documentation for each respective [MongoDB Search operators](operators-ref).

> **Note:** You can also use the `token` type to index
> string fields for pre-filtering your data for [$vectorSearch](pipe.$vectorSearch)
> queries. To learn more, see [MongoDB Vector Search](fts-vector-search).

When you index a field as the `token` type, you must index that field
as `string` type also to query the text value using operators such as
[text](text-ref), [Phrase](phrase-ref), etc. For the following operators,
you don't need to index the field as `string` type also to query the
text value in the field:

- [equals](equals-ref)

- [in](in-ref)

- [range](range-ref)

> **Note:** We do not recommend indexing a field with both the `stringFacet` (deprecated)
> and `token` types, unless you require a different normalizer for the `token`
> type for a use case other than faceting. With this index definition, MongoDB Search
> uses the `stringFacet` definition for faceting.

When you index a field as `token` type, MongoDB Search indexes the terms in
the string as a single token (searchable term) and stores them in a
columnar storage for efficient filtering or sort operations. You
can use a [normalizer](ref-built-in-normalizers) to transform the
token. By default, the normalizer is set to `none` and so MongoDB Search
indexes strings in their original form.

The major difference between the MongoDB Search `string` and `token` types is
that MongoDB Search creates one or more tokens for fields indexed as `string`
type whereas MongoDB Search creates only a single token for fields indexed as the
`token` type.

If a string being indexed as a `token` field type exceeds 8181
characters, MongoDB Search truncates it to 8181 characters before indexing.

